Exercise 2:

The file melanoma.dat, which is stored along with a description in the Stud.IP folder “Data”, contains data of a clinical study at the Department of Plastic Surgery, University Hospital of Odense, Denmark. 205 patients were observed during the years 1962 to 1977 after a skin cancer operation (removal of the tumor and the surrounding skin), either up to the end of the year 1977 or their early death.

(a)

Write a function lifetable <- function(time,delta,grid){...} in R to imple- ment the life-table method. The argument time corresponds to the event times of the n individuals, delta is a censoring indicator and grid contains the points used for discretization of the time axis. For a given set of data, the function should return the conditional probability of experiencing the event in each interval, the estimated survival function at the start of each interval, and the estimated density and hazard rate at the midpoint of each interval.

Answer:

lifetable <- function(time,delta,grid)
{
  q <- length(grid)-1 # number of intervals
  n <- length(time)   # number of observations
  
  d <- numeric(q)     # number of events in intervals
  Y <- rep(n,q+1)     # vector of risk set
  w <- numeric(q)     # number of censored observations in intervals
  h <- numeric(q)     # lengths of intervals
  
  for(k in 1:q)
  {
    # number of events in interval a_k
    d[k] <- sum(delta[time>=grid[k] & time<grid[k+1]])
    
    # number of censored observations in interval a_k
    #(number of all time points in interval minus number of events in interval
    w[k] <- length(delta[time>=grid[k] & time<grid[k+1]])-d[k]
    
    # risk set <- risk set in previous interval minus events minus censored observations
    Y[k+1] <- Y[k] - d[k] - w[k]
    
    # lengths of intervals
    h[k] <- grid[k+1] - grid[k]
  }
  
  cp.event <- survivor <- density <- hazard <- numeric(q)
  
  # Estimators
  cp.event <- d / (Y[-(q+1)] - w/2)
  survivor <- cumprod(1-cp.event)
  density <- ( c(1,survivor[-q]) - survivor ) / h
  hazard <- 2*cp.event / (h * (2-cp.event))
  
  # Extent estimators for plotting
  cp.event <- c(cp.event,cp.event[q])
  survivor <- c(1,survivor)
  density <- c(density,density[q])
  hazard <- c(hazard,hazard[q])
  
  # Save results in list and return
  erg <- list(cp.event=cp.event,
              survivor=survivor,
              density=density,
              hazard=hazard)
  return(erg)
}

Exercise 3:

Several proposals for computing pointwise confidence intervals for values of the survival function do exist.

(a)

Recall the data file melanoma.dat that was analysed in exercise 2. In R, use the survfit() function from the package survival to compute the Kaplan-Meier estimate of the survivor function and compare various pointwise \(95\%\) confidence intervals that are available in the option conf.type.

Answer:

(b)

Use the delta method that was introduced in the lectures to derive the asymptotic variance of \(ln(− ln( \hat{S}(t))\).

Answer:

The delta method is given as: \[ Var(f(x)) = Var(x) \cdot \Bigg( \dfrac{\delta(f(x))}{\delta x} \Bigg)^{2} \]

Applied to our problem we get:

\[\begin{align} \mathrm{Var}\Big( \mathrm{ln} ( -\mathrm{ln} ( \hat{S}(t) ) \Big) &= \mathrm{Var} \Big( \mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) ) \Big) \cdot \Bigg( \dfrac{\delta \big( \mathrm{ln}( -\mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) ) \big) }{\delta \Big( \mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) ) \Big)} \Bigg)^{2} \\ &= \mathrm{Var} \Big( \mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) ) \Big) \cdot \dfrac{1}{\mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) )^{2} } \\ &= \sum_{t_{i} \leq t} \dfrac{d_{k}}{ n_{k} (n_{k} - d_{k})} \cdot \dfrac{1}{\mathrm{ln}( \hat{S}(t) )^{2} } \end{align}\]

(c)

Based on the result obtained in (b) give a corresponding asymptotic \(100(1 − \alpha)\%\) confidence interval for \(S(t)\).

Answer:

CI for \(\hat{S}(t)\) given by:

\[ CI_{\pm} = \mathrm{ln} \big( \mathrm{-ln} (\hat{S}(t) \big) \pm z_{\frac{\alpha}{2}} \cdot \sqrt{ \mathrm{Var}\Big( \mathrm{ln} ( -\mathrm{ln} ( \hat{S}(t) ) \Big) }\]
